FordGoBike-dataset Data Exploration¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing bike-share trip durations in San Francisco during Febraury 2019. it includes attributes(like. start_station_id,end_station_id ,gender ,customer type ,....) for approximately 184,000 bike-share records.

In [9]:
def get_nearest_station(null_stations_latitude,stations_coordinates):    
    station_mapping = {}

    for i in null_stations_latitude:
        lowset_diff_loc = 1000
        nearst_loc = 0
        for x in stations_coordinates:
            current_diff_loc = abs(x - i)
            if current_diff_loc < lowset_diff_loc:
                lowset_diff_loc = current_diff_loc
                nearst_loc = x
        station_mapping[i]= nearst_loc
    return station_mapping

Features Extraction¶

In [21]:
# convert duration_sec for each record into hours based
# get weekday , hour for each record from date
# get member Age from date and member_birth_year

df_orgin['duration_hour(hrs)'] = round(df_orgin['duration_sec']/3600 ,2)
df_orgin['duration_min(min)'] = round(df_orgin['duration_sec']/60 ,2)

df_orgin['weekday'] = df_orgin['start_time'].dt.dayofweek
df_orgin['weekday'] = [calendar.day_name[i] for i in df_orgin['weekday']]

df_orgin['start_hour'] = df_orgin['start_time'].dt.hour.astype('category')
df_orgin['start_station_id'] = df_orgin['start_station_id'].astype('category')
df_orgin['end_station_id'] = df_orgin['start_station_id'].astype('category')

df_orgin['member_age(years)'] = df_orgin['start_time'].dt.year - df_orgin['member_birth_year']

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 Bikes' rental records in the dataset for February 2019 in San Francisco with 9 features (start_station_name, end_station_name, weekday, start_hour, bike_share_for_all_trip, member_gender, member_age(years), user_type and duration_min(min)).

Most variables are Categorical, but the variables member_age(years) and duration_min(min) are numeric variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out how features like start stations locations ,user type , weekdays & member ages are affecting bikes' rental_durations and bikes' rental trips number in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I am expecting that start station locations & end station locations , weekday, user type will have the strongest effect on trips durations and number of trips. for example , subscribers are more likely riding more than customers and bikes rental records more likely to be higher in normal weekdays than weekends.

I also think that the gender and member age could affect the bikes' rental_durations. for example, I think younger riders are more than older riders and their rentals have longer rental duration.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: Bike Trip durations: duration_hour(hrs).

From above graphs we can observe:

  • Bikes rentals on workdays are approximatly double the rentals during weekends.it is more likely it is due to working schedule. The highest Bikes rentals are on Thursday.
  • Bikes rentals have 2 peak intervals during the day.
    • 1st Peak interval 2 hours in morning between 08:00am to 10:00am. it's more likely that riders are going to their work.
    • 2nd peak interval 32 hours in evening between 04:00pm to 07:00pm. it's more likely that riders are returning from their work.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip durations & memebers' Ages variable took on a large range of values with right skewed distribution, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked more likely normally distributed, with mean riders' ages around 32 - 34 years old, and mean of trips durations around 9 minutes.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • I have observed have 72 records for Ages more than 100 years old , those outliers may be due to data enteries issue. Thus , i have exculded these records from our data sets.

  • For geneder feature , 3652 records are found annotated as 'Others' which may be due to data enteries issue. Thus , I computed 'Others' by the most gender type( Male or Female) per the record's Start station.

  • 329 stations are found in our data set. while we are intersted in the top stations with the highest trips (most bikes Rentals). Thus , i have filtered our data set based on the Top 7 stations with records more than 2500.

# compute the logarithm of age & trip durations to make multivariate plotting easier

def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

df_top_rmv_outliers['log_duration_min'] = df_top_rmv_outliers['duration_min(min)'].apply(log_trans)
df_top_rmv_outliers['log_member_age(years)'] = df_top_rmv_outliers['member_age(years)'].apply(log_trans)
